# ============================================================
# MAGICTHON — .cursorrules
# Meme generation app · React + Node.js · Build day rules
# ============================================================

## What We're Building
A modern meme creation tool for Magicthon hackathon.
Users upload a photo → AI analyzes it → suggests 6 meme formats →
user edits on canvas → exports PNG → shares via unique link →
anyone can react live, no signup needed.

## Stack (Non-Negotiable)
- Frontend  : React + JavaScript (no TypeScript), Vite
- UI Library: PrimeReact — use its components as the base, override with CSS
- Styling   : Native CSS files (one per component) + global CSS variables
- Animation : Framer Motion for page transitions and micro-interactions
- Canvas    : Konva.js + react-konva for the meme canvas editor
- State     : Redux Toolkit — all async API calls via createAsyncThunk
- Testing   : Playwright for end-to-end automation
- Backend   : Node.js + Express
- Database  : Supabase (Postgres + Realtime + Storage)
- AI        : OpenAI GPT-4o (vision) via backend proxy
- Deploy    : Vercel (frontend) + Railway or Render (backend)

## Project Structure (Flat, Predictable — Do Not Deviate)
frontend/
  src/
    components/         # UI components, one per file, <150 lines
      ComponentName.jsx
      ComponentName.css   ← paired CSS file, same name
    pages/              # Route-level components
      PageName.jsx
      PageName.css
    hooks/              # All data-fetching and stateful logic
    services/           # API calls to backend (never call API from components)
    lib/                # Konva helpers, template definitions, utils
    constants/          # Template configs, color palettes, font list
    store/              # Global state (Zustand)
    styles/
      globals.css         ← CSS custom properties (design tokens), resets
      primereact-theme.css ← ALL PrimeReact overrides go here, nowhere else
  public/
backend/
  src/
    routes/             # Express route handlers (thin — logic in services)
    services/           # Business logic (meme, ai, storage, reaction)
    lib/                # Supabase client, OpenAI client
    middleware/         # Error handler, rate limiter
  index.js

## CSS Architecture Rules (Critical — Read Before Writing Any CSS)

### File Pairing Rule
Every component gets its own CSS file with the same name.
  UploadZone.jsx  →  UploadZone.css
  MemeCard.jsx    →  MemeCard.css
Import it at the top of the component: import './UploadZone.css'
Never put one component's styles in another component's CSS file.

### CSS Custom Properties (globals.css is the single source of truth)
All design tokens are defined once in src/styles/globals.css as CSS variables.
Reference them everywhere — never hardcode a color, spacing, or font value.
Example: use var(--color-accent) not #f5e642 in any component CSS file.

### Class Naming Convention — BEM-lite
Use descriptive, component-scoped class names to avoid collisions:
  .upload-zone { }              ← block
  .upload-zone__droparea { }    ← element
  .upload-zone__droparea--active { }  ← modifier
Never use generic class names like .card, .button, .title alone.
Always prefix with the component name: .meme-card__title, .editor-toolbar__btn.

### PrimeReact Override Strategy
PrimeReact components are the BASE — use them for structure and accessibility.
Override their appearance in src/styles/primereact-theme.css ONLY.
NEVER write PrimeReact overrides inside a component's own CSS file.
Use PrimeReact's CSS variable system where possible:
  :root { --p-button-background: var(--color-accent); }
For surgical overrides use their generated class names:
  .p-button.p-button-primary { background: var(--color-accent); }

### Which PrimeReact Components to Use (and for What)
- p-fileupload (headless mode)  → photo upload, we fully control the UI
- p-button                      → all buttons (CTA, toolbar, reactions)
- p-slider                      → font size control in canvas editor
- p-dialog                      → share modal, webcam modal
- p-toast                       → copy-to-clipboard feedback, error alerts
- p-skeleton                    → loading placeholders on suggestion cards
- p-progressbar                 → optional upload progress
- p-tooltip                     → hover hints on toolbar buttons
For anything else: build it as a plain React component with native CSS.
Do NOT use PrimeReact for layout (no p-grid, p-flex) — use CSS Grid/Flexbox.

### Spacing System (use these values only — define as CSS vars)
--space-1: 4px
--space-2: 8px
--space-3: 12px
--space-4: 16px
--space-5: 24px
--space-6: 32px
--space-7: 48px
--space-8: 64px

### Responsive Breakpoints
--bp-mobile:  375px
--bp-tablet:  768px
--bp-desktop: 1200px
Mobile-first always: base styles are for 375px, media queries add desktop styles.
  @media (min-width: 768px) { ... }   ← tablet and up
  @media (min-width: 1200px) { ... }  ← desktop and up

## Naming Conventions
- Components    : PascalCase  (MemeCard.jsx, CanvasEditor.jsx)
- CSS files     : PascalCase matching component (MemeCard.css)
- CSS classes   : BEM-lite kebab-case (see above)
- Hooks         : camelCase starting with "use" (useMemeSuggestions.js)
- Services      : camelCase ending with "Service" (memeService.js)
- API routes    : kebab-case  (/api/meme-suggestions, /api/share)
- Constants     : SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for values, camelCase for objects
- Files         : max 150 lines — split if longer

## Architecture Rules
1. Components only handle rendering and local UI state
2. All async logic lives in custom hooks
3. All API calls live in /services — never fetch() inside a component
4. All business logic lives in backend /services — never in route handlers
5. Templates are data (config objects in /constants/templates.js)
   — never hardcoded layouts, never static images
6. Supabase is only called from the backend — never from frontend directly
7. OpenAI is only called from the backend — API key never touches frontend

## The Template System (Critical — Read Before Building)
Every meme template is a config object, not an image:
{
  id: "drake",
  name: "Drake Approves",
  layout: "split-vertical",
  photoPlacement: "background" | "zone",
  textZones: [
    { id: "top", label: "Rejection", defaultText: "...", style: {...} },
    { id: "bottom", label: "Approval", defaultText: "...", style: {...} }
  ],
  overlayStyle: "classic" | "minimal" | "editorial"
}
The LLM returns a template ID + text for each zone.
The canvas renders it dynamically from the config.
Never hard-code layout logic per template — it must be data-driven.

## AI / Prompt Rules
- The vision prompt MUST instruct the model to:
  1. First describe the photo (expression, context, energy, setting)
  2. Then pick a template ID from the provided list
  3. Then write top text and bottom text specific to THIS photo
  4. Return structured JSON only — no prose, no markdown fences
- The backend validates the JSON shape before returning to frontend
- Always include a fallback if the LLM returns malformed output

## UI/UX Non-Negotiables (Priority 0)
- Every interactive element needs hover + active + focus states (in CSS)
- Every async operation needs a loading state — never freeze the UI
- Loading states are creative moments (witty copy, p-skeleton cards)
- Use Framer Motion for: page transitions, card reveals, button feedback
- Mobile-first always — design for 375px, enhance for desktop
- No hardcoded spacing — always use var(--space-N)
- No placeholder copy anywhere — every label is intentional and witty
- The upload zone, loading screen, and share page each get special care
- Meme suggestions appear with a staggered animation (not all at once)
- Canvas editor feels snappy — dragging text must never lag

## Visual Identity (Define All of These in globals.css)
Direction: Dark, punchy, editorial — like a creative tool, not a form.

--color-bg:          #0a0a0a;   /* page background */
--color-surface:     #141414;   /* panels, sidebars */
--color-card:        #1c1c1c;   /* cards, modals */
--color-border:      #2a2a2a;   /* all borders */
--color-accent:      #f5e642;   /* electric yellow — use sparingly */
--color-accent-dark: #c9ba1a;   /* accent hover state */
--color-text-primary:   #f0f0f0;
--color-text-secondary: #888888;
--color-danger:      #ff4444;

--font-display: 'Bebas Neue', sans-serif;   /* headlines, nav, labels */
--font-body:    'DM Sans', sans-serif;      /* all UI text */
--font-meme:    'Impact', 'Anton', sans-serif; /* inside the canvas only */

--radius-sm:  4px;
--radius-md:  8px;
--radius-lg:  12px;
--radius-pill: 999px;

No box-shadow on dark surfaces — use border: 1px solid var(--color-border) instead.

## State Management (Redux Toolkit)
One store, slice-per-feature pattern. All API calls use createAsyncThunk.
store/
  index.js              ← configureStore, root reducer
  uploadSlice.js        ← photo file, preview URL, upload status
  suggestSlice.js       ← suggestions[], loading, error + analyzePhoto thunk
  editorSlice.js        ← selected template, text values, canvas history (undo stack)
  shareSlice.js         ← shareId, shareUrl, reactions + shareMeme / addReaction thunks

Rules for every slice:
- State shape is flat — no nested objects more than 1 level deep
- Every createAsyncThunk has all 3 cases handled: pending, fulfilled, rejected
- Loading state uses the string enum pattern: 'idle' | 'loading' | 'succeeded' | 'failed'
- Error state is always a string (message only), never a raw Error object
- Selectors are defined at the bottom of each slice file and exported
- Components use useSelector with named selectors — never access store shape directly

Example pattern (follow this in every slice):
  export const analyzePhoto = createAsyncThunk(
    'suggest/analyzePhoto',
    async (file, { rejectWithValue }) => {
      try {
        return await memeService.analyzeMeme(file)
      } catch (err) {
        return rejectWithValue(err.message)
      }
    }
  )
  // In extraReducers:
  .addCase(analyzePhoto.pending, (state) => {
    state.status = 'loading'; state.error = null
  })
  .addCase(analyzePhoto.fulfilled, (state, action) => {
    state.status = 'succeeded'; state.suggestions = action.payload
  })
  .addCase(analyzePhoto.rejected, (state, action) => {
    state.status = 'failed'; state.error = action.payload
  })

## API Contract (Backend Endpoints)
POST /api/analyze        — accepts image, returns 6 meme suggestions (JSON)
POST /api/share          — saves meme to Supabase, returns shareId + URL
GET  /api/share/:id      — returns meme data for the share page
POST /api/react/:id      — adds a reaction (emoji + count)
GET  /api/react/:id      — returns current reaction counts

## Error Handling
- Backend: all errors go through a central error middleware
- Frontend: every hook catches errors and exposes an `error` state
- Use PrimeReact's p-toast for all user-facing error messages
- If the LLM fails: toast error + "Try again" button
- If the LLM returns malformed JSON: retry once silently, then toast error
- If Supabase is slow: show optimistic UI, sync in background
- Never let the app crash silently — always surface something to the user

## Code Quality Rules
- No console.log in any committed code (use a debug flag if needed)
- No hardcoded colors, spacing, or font values — always use CSS vars
- No hardcoded API URLs — use environment variables only
- No API keys anywhere in frontend code
- Max file size: 150 lines — if longer, split into smaller modules
- Every async function uses try/catch
- Named exports everywhere (except page-level components)

## Cursor-Specific Instructions
- Always follow the pattern of the nearest existing similar component
- When creating a new component, create its paired CSS file at the same time
- New CSS variables go in globals.css first, then reference them
- PrimeReact overrides go ONLY in primereact-theme.css, never elsewhere
- When adding a new API call, add it to the relevant /services file — never inline
- Do not modify files outside the scope of the current task
- Do not add dependencies not in this rules file without asking
- Keep Framer Motion variants defined at the top of each component file

## Environment Variables
Frontend (.env):
  VITE_API_URL=http://localhost:3001

Backend (.env):
  OPENAI_API_KEY=
  SUPABASE_URL=
  SUPABASE_SERVICE_KEY=
  PORT=3001
  FRONTEND_URL=http://localhost:5173

## Do NOT
- Use TypeScript (this project is JavaScript only)
- Use Zustand, MobX, or Context for global state — Redux Toolkit only
- Use Tailwind CSS or styled-components
- Write inline styles (style={{ }}) except for dynamic Konva/canvas values
- Use PrimeReact for layout (no p-grid, p-flex) — use CSS Grid/Flexbox
- Put PrimeReact overrides inside component CSS files — use primereact-theme.css
- Hardcode any color, spacing, or font — use CSS variables from globals.css
- Call Supabase or OpenAI from the frontend
- Put logic inside route handlers
- Create files longer than 150 lines
- Use default exports except for page components
- Add auth or login of any kind
- Use static images as meme templates
- Use raw canvas API — use Konva/react-konva
- Skip loading states for any async operation
- Use Inter, Roboto, or Arial anywhere in the UI


